hook.real_world_problem:
Now that you can write generic methods (Topic 9.2), try writing a `max` method that returns the largest element of any list:

```java
public static <T> T max(List<T> list) {
    T result = list.get(0);
    for (T item : list) {
        if (item > result) { ... }  // COMPILE ERROR — can't use > on T!
        if (item.compareTo(result) > 0) { ... }  // COMPILE ERROR — T has no compareTo()!
    }
    return result;
}
```

The compiler rightfully complains: `T` could be ANYTHING — a Product, a Scanner, a Thread. You can't compare arbitrary objects.

**With an upper bound:**

```java
public static <T extends Comparable<T>> T max(List<T> list) {
    //               ↑ bound: T MUST implement Comparable<T>
    T result = list.get(0);
    for (T item : list) {
        if (item.compareTo(result) > 0) result = item;  // NOW COMPILES!
    }
    return result;
}
```

The bound `<T extends Comparable<T>>` tells Java: 'T can be any type, AS LONG AS it implements Comparable<T>'. Now:
- The compiler KNOWS T has `compareTo()` — allows the call
- PREVENTS calling `max()` with a non-comparable type (e.g., `max(List<Product>)` fails unless Product implements Comparable)

```java
max(List.of(3, 1, 4))           // OK — Integer implements Comparable<Integer>
max(List.of("Raj", "Aisha"))    // OK — String implements Comparable<String>
max(List.of(new Scanner(System.in)))  // COMPILE ERROR — Scanner doesn't implement Comparable
```

This is exactly how `Collections.max()` and `Collections.min()` are implemented in Java's standard library.

concept_explanation.upper_bound_syntax:
**Upper bound syntax — `extends`:**

```java
// Class with bound: T must be a Number (or subclass)
class NumberBox<T extends Number> {
    private T value;
    NumberBox(T v) { value = v; }

    // Can call Number methods on T:
    double asDouble() { return value.doubleValue(); }  // Number has doubleValue()
    int    asInt()    { return value.intValue(); }     // Number has intValue()

    boolean isPositive() { return value.doubleValue() > 0; }
}

// Usage:
NumberBox<Integer> intBox = new NumberBox<>(42);     // OK — Integer extends Number
NumberBox<Double>  dblBox = new NumberBox<>(3.14);   // OK — Double extends Number
NumberBox<String>  strBox = new NumberBox<>("hi");   // COMPILE ERROR — String not a Number
```

**The key insight**: inside the class, you can call any method that `Number` declares on the value — because the compiler KNOWS T is at least a Number.

**Note**: in generics, `extends` means both 'extends' (class hierarchy) AND 'implements' (interface). `<T extends Comparable<T>>` means T implements Comparable, even though Comparable is an interface.

concept_explanation.comparable_bound:
**The most common bound: `Comparable<T>`**

```java
// Find the maximum of any Comparable list:
public static <T extends Comparable<T>> T max(List<T> list) {
    if (list.isEmpty()) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Empty list");
    T result = list.get(0);
    for (T item : list) {
        if (item.compareTo(result) > 0) result = item;
    }
    return result;
}

// Find min:
public static <T extends Comparable<T>> T min(List<T> list) {
    if (list.isEmpty()) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Empty list");
    T result = list.get(0);
    for (T item : list) {
        if (item.compareTo(result) < 0) result = item;
    }
    return result;
}

// Sort in place (selection sort):
public static <T extends Comparable<T>> void sort(List<T> list) {
    for (int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++) {
        int minIdx = i;
        for (int j = i+1; j < list.size(); j++) {
            if (list.get(j).compareTo(list.get(minIdx)) < 0) minIdx = j;
        }
        // swap i and minIdx
        T temp = list.get(i);
        list.set(i, list.get(minIdx));
        list.set(minIdx, temp);
    }
}

// Usage:
System.out.println(max(Arrays.asList(3, 1, 4, 1, 5)));         // 5
System.out.println(min(Arrays.asList("Priya", "Aisha", "Raj"))); // Aisha
```

concept_explanation.number_bound:
**`Number` bound** — for numeric types only:

```java
// Sum any list of numbers:
public static <T extends Number> double sum(List<T> numbers) {
    double total = 0;
    for (T n : numbers) {
        total += n.doubleValue();  // Number.doubleValue() is available
    }
    return total;
}

// Average:
public static <T extends Number> double average(List<T> numbers) {
    if (numbers.isEmpty()) return 0;
    return sum(numbers) / numbers.size();
}

// Usage:
List<Integer> ints = Arrays.asList(10, 20, 30);
List<Double> doubles = Arrays.asList(1.5, 2.5, 3.5);
List<Long> longs = Arrays.asList(100L, 200L, 300L);

System.out.println(sum(ints));     // 60.0
System.out.println(sum(doubles));  // 7.5
System.out.println(sum(longs));    // 600.0
```

Number's methods: `doubleValue()`, `intValue()`, `longValue()`, `floatValue()`.

concept_explanation.multiple_bounds:
**Multiple bounds — `&`**:

```java
// T must be both Comparable AND Cloneable:
<T extends Comparable<T> & Cloneable>

// More common: T extends a class AND implements an interface:
<T extends Number & Comparable<T>>
```

Rules:
- At most ONE class bound (must be first if present)
- Any number of interface bounds (after the class)
- Separate with `&`

```java
// Useful pattern: Comparable AND some custom interface
interface Printable { void print(); }

public static <T extends Comparable<T> & Printable> T maxAndPrint(List<T> list) {
    T result = max(list);
    result.print();    // Printable is available
    return result;     // Comparable was used to find it
}
```

**Common real bound: `T extends Number & Comparable<T>`**

```java
// T must be a numeric type that's also sortable:
<T extends Number & Comparable<T>>
// Matches: Integer, Long, Double, Float (all extend Number AND implement Comparable)
// Doesn't match: BigDecimal (extends Number but Comparable impl differs)
```

concept_explanation.bounded_on_class:
**Bounded type parameter on a class:**

```java
// SortedBox only accepts Comparable types:
class SortedBox<T extends Comparable<T>> {
    private List<T> items = new ArrayList<>();

    public void add(T item) {
        items.add(item);
        Collections.sort(items);  // Can sort because T is Comparable
    }

    public T min() { return items.isEmpty() ? null : items.get(0); }
    public T max() { return items.isEmpty() ? null : items.get(items.size() - 1); }
    public List<T> getItems() { return Collections.unmodifiableList(items); }
}

// Usage:
SortedBox<Integer> intBox = new SortedBox<>();
intBox.add(5); intBox.add(2); intBox.add(8); intBox.add(1);
System.out.println(intBox.getItems()); // [1, 2, 5, 8] — auto-sorted!
System.out.println(intBox.min());      // 1
System.out.println(intBox.max());      // 8

// Works for any Comparable:
SortedBox<String> strBox = new SortedBox<>();
strBox.add("Priya"); strBox.add("Aisha"); strBox.add("Raj");
System.out.println(strBox.getItems()); // [Aisha, Priya, Raj]

// This doesn't compile:
SortedBox<Product> productBox = new SortedBox<>();  // COMPILE ERROR unless Product implements Comparable
```

concept_explanation.clamp_and_range_methods:
**Practical bounded patterns:**

```java
// Clamp: keep value within [min, max]
public static <T extends Comparable<T>> T clamp(T value, T min, T max) {
    if (value.compareTo(min) < 0) return min;
    if (value.compareTo(max) > 0) return max;
    return value;
}
// clamp(15, 0, 10) = 10;  clamp(5, 0, 10) = 5;  clamp(-3, 0, 10) = 0

// isBetween: is value in range [min, max]?
public static <T extends Comparable<T>> boolean isBetween(T value, T min, T max) {
    return value.compareTo(min) >= 0 && value.compareTo(max) <= 0;
}
// isBetween(75, 60, 100) = true
// isBetween(55, 60, 100) = false

// Numeric statistics — both Number and Comparable
public static <T extends Number & Comparable<T>> T median(List<T> list) {
    List<T> sorted = new ArrayList<>(list);
    Collections.sort(sorted);  // OK — Comparable
    return sorted.get(sorted.size() / 2);
}
```

concept_explanation.reading_java_signatures:
**Reading real Java library signatures:**

```java
// Collections.sort:
public static <T extends Comparable<? super T>> void sort(List<T> list)
// '<? super T>' is a wildcard (Topic 9.4) — means T or any supertype of T

// Collections.max:
public static <T extends Object & Comparable<? super T>> T max(Collection<? extends T> coll)
// 'extends Object' ensures type erasure produces Object not Comparable

// TreeMap constructor:
public class TreeMap<K extends Comparable<? super K>, V> ...
// K must be Comparable — TreeMap keeps keys sorted

// Understanding NOW (wildcards in 9.4):
// The ?super part allows max(Collection<Integer>) where T is Number
// Because Integer extends Number extends Object which implements Comparable
```

The wildcards (`? super T`, `? extends T`) are Topic 9.4. But the core `<T extends Comparable<T>>` pattern you fully understand now.

